	</tr>
	<tr>
		<td colspan="2"><hr class="sep" />What socram8888 suggested is called the PowerPak. And it uses CF because SD's SPI is far slower than CF's parallel ATA without some hardware assistance. Besides, to make something a PowerPak, even if it's just for one mapper, you still need a boot ROM and an SRAM the size of PRG ROM. Munchausen is supposed to be cheap.

		

		</td>
	</tr>
	</table>


	<hr width="85%" />

	<table width="85%" cellspacing="3" cellpadding="0" border="0" align="center">
	<tr>
		<td width="10%" nowrap="nowrap">Author:&nbsp;</td>
		<td><b>mic_</b> [ Sat Mar 05, 2011 1:32 am ]</td>
	</tr>
	<tr>
		<td width="10%" nowrap="nowrap">Post subject:&nbsp;</td>
		<td><b></b></td>
	</tr>
	<tr>
		<td colspan="2"><hr class="sep" /><div class="quotetitle"><b>Quote:</b></div><div class="quotecontent">And it uses CF because SD's SPI is far slower than CF's parallel ATA without some hardware assistance.</div>
<br />SD SPI mode is really slow because you need to do a write for every read. In native mode you don't need to do that, with the drawback that you can read only 4 bits at a time. I haven't tried reading SD cards on the NES - but I have on the SNES, and I can read files at upwards of 200 kB/s with good cards and some minimal hardware assistance (no DMA or anything, just a kind-of latch that combines two 4-bit data reads into a byte that gets placed on the bus at the next write). I'm not familiar enough with the ATA protocol to say which is faster or easier to implement.

		

		</td>
	</tr>
	</table>


	<hr width="85%" />

	<table width="85%" cellspacing="3" cellpadding="0" border="0" align="center">
	<tr>
